<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-toxero-compare" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§07</span><span class="idx__t">An honest read</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="max-width:24ch;margin-bottom:12px;">Where each platform actually wins.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 36px;max-width:60ch;">Not marketing talking points &mdash; the real differences that matter when you&rsquo;re deciding. The decision is rarely about features; it&rsquo;s about ecosystem, team, and accountant fit.</p>
    <table class="cmp" data-viz="comparison-table" data-viz-state="FINAL">
      <caption class="sr-only">QuickBooks Online versus Xero, by capability, from an independent Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor firm.</caption>
      <thead><tr><th scope="col">Capability</th><th scope="col" class="us">QuickBooks Online</th><th scope="col">Xero</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {%- for row in compare %}
        <tr><th scope="row">{{ row.dim | safe }}</th><td class="us" data-col="QuickBooks Online"><strong>{{ row.qb | safe }}</strong></td><td data-col="Xero">{{ row.xero | safe }}</td></tr>
        {%- endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <div class="prose" style="margin-top:40px;">
      <h3>Where Xero wins</h3>
      <p>Multi-currency handling is cleaner and sits at a lower price tier. Unlimited users on every plan. The fixed-asset register is native, where QuickBooks needs an add-on. The reconciliation interface is opinionated and many teams prefer it. Bank-feed reliability is comparable, and in some regions slightly better.</p>
      <h3>Where QuickBooks wins</h3>
      <p>The U.S. accountant ecosystem is far larger &mdash; Intuit reports more than 700,000 ProAdvisors and accountants. The app marketplace is deeper for U.S. workflows. Built-in payroll is mature and native, where Xero relies on Gusto, ADP, or similar. Inventory and cost-of-goods tracking is native, where Xero leans on paid add-ons. U.S.-centric workflows &mdash; sales tax, 1099s, U.S. banking &mdash; are more native.</p>
      <h3>Where they&rsquo;re effectively tied</h3>
      <p>Core double-entry bookkeeping, basic AR/AP, invoicing, expense management, and the mobile apps. For a single-entity U.S. business with standard needs, both platforms do the fundamental job well. The decision is rarely about features &mdash; it&rsquo;s about ecosystem, team, and accountant fit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

